In more complex circumstances, I might consider making the intake mechanism more robust by using a function that captures a generic path so that 'any' file could be loaded. This is also a good opportunity to start getting familiar with our dataset.

I usually start by trying to classify the variables into subsets, such as:
1) Numerical Continuous
2) Numerical Discrete
3) Categorical Unordered
4) Categorical Ordered
5) Dates or Times
6) Text

I then note the number of rows and columns in the data frame.
I am reviewing the data types of our features and noting missing values in the rows.

Data Cleaning

The entire data cleaning process serves to prepare our dataset for intake into the machine learning model.

We begin the data cleaning process by using the observations noted in the opening steps of our framework.
I am cleaning missing values within the dataset, removing outliers, removing bad data, and removing unnecessary attributes.

I have chosen to remove the below features because they contain trivial or non-predictive value.
['name', 'email', 'phone-number', 'credit_card', 'country', 'assigned_room_type','reserved_room_type','reservation_status', 'reservation_status_date']

Next, we encode binary representations (0's and 1's) for categorical features and map month objects to the ordinal numerical representation.
We use one-hot encoding to split categorical variables into separate columns and remove the original features that were made redundant during one-hot encoding.

We use casting for type consistency in the dataset as many of the feature's types changed to int32 and int8 during the data cleaning process.
Again, we finish by running a quality check on our dataset by calling the data frame and dataframe.info().

It might be best practice to create a separate dataset to store the clean data, but the computer scientist within me always questions the efficiency of duplicating the dataset in memory. On the other hand, the engineer within me always considers the value of building redundancy into the process.

At this point, I would also consider normalizing the data as it's part of my framework.

In [7]:
#lamda functions for encoding categorical attributes to binary representations (0's and 1's)
x = lambda a: 0 if pd.isnull(a) else 1
y = lambda a: 0 if a == 0 else 1
z = lambda a: 'International' if a != 'PRT' else 'Local'

#cleaning missing values within the dataset
df['country'].fillna(df['country'].mode()[0], inplace = True)
df['company'] = df['company'].apply(x)
df['agent'] = df['agent'].apply(x)


#encoding categorical attributes to binary representation (0's and 1's)
df['previous_cancellations'] = df['previous_cancellations'].apply(y)
df['booking_changes'] = df['booking_changes'].apply(y)
df['location'] = df['country'].apply(z)
df['hotel'] = df['hotel'].replace(['Resort Hotel', 'City Hotel'], [0,1])

#removing outliers and bad data
df.dropna(subset=['children'], inplace=True)
df.drop(df[df['adr'] < 0].index, inplace = True)
df.drop(df[df['adr'] >= 510].index, inplace = True)
df.drop(df[df['adults'] < 1].index, inplace = True)

#removing unnecessary attributes from our dataset
df.drop(['name', 'email', 'phone-number', 'credit_card', 'country', 'assigned_room_type','reserved_room_type','reservation_status', 'reservation_status_date'], axis=1, inplace=True)
In [8]:
#mapping month object to the ordinal numerical representation
months = {'arrival_date_month':{'January':1,'February':2,'March':3, 'April':4, 'May':5, 'June':6,'July':7,'August':8, 'September':9,'October':10,'November':11, 'December':12}}
df.replace(months, inplace=True)

#One-Hot Encoding for Categorical Features
encoderLst = ['meal', 'market_segment', 'distribution_channel', 'deposit_type', 'customer_type', 'location']
for i in encoderLst:
    hot = pd.get_dummies(df[i], prefix=i).astype('int64')
    df = df.join(hot)

#Removing those attributes that were made redundant during the One-Hot Encoding for Categorical Features
df.drop(['meal', 'market_segment', 'distribution_channel', 'deposit_type', 'customer_type', 'location'], axis= 1, inplace=True)

#Casting for type consistency in dataset
df['children'] = df.children.astype('int64')
df['agent'] = df.agent.astype('int64')
df['company'] = df.company.astype('int64')
df['hotel'] = df.hotel.astype('int64')
df['arrival_date_month'] = df.arrival_date_month.astype('int64')

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient

We create three views of Pearson's Correlation Coefficient:
1) correlation table
2) heatmap visual of the correlation table
3) a sorted listing of our (y) variable Vs. the (x) variables that might be important to predicting cancellation.
This is done for both the training and testing datasets.

We remember that Pearson's Correlation Coefficient ranges between [-1 and 1] where negative one indicates a perfect negative relationship between the variables and positive one indicates a perfect positive relationship between the variables. We also remember the well-known adage, "correlation does not imply causation".

It's now safe to make some predictions about those columns that might be important in predicting cancellation.

I rely on our third view of Pearson's Correlation Coefficient.

Promising (x) variables from the testing set:
deposit_type_Non Refund (0.485994)
location_Local (0.340415)
lead_time (0.293998)
previous_cancellations (0.274345)

Promising (x) variables from the training set:

It's also important to note those (x) variables that might not be important in predicting cancellation by looking at the negative values at the bottom of third view of Pearson's Correlation Coefficient.

At this step in the framework, I would normally consider pruning the (x) variables manually or using a forward/backward stepwise algorithm for feature selection. This also requires running many model iterations using different sets of (x) variables to aid in finding the optimal balance between performance, variance, and bias.

Machine Learning Model

I have chosen to implement a Decision Tree Classifier machine learning model.

My thought process for model selection:
1) Categorical or Numerical: The categorical nature of the (y) variable led me to choose a model within the Supervised Learning-Classification subset of machine learning model options.
2) Algorithm — space and time complexity: For a time sensitive project, we can't afford to wait long amounts of time for model iterations and testing.
3) Dataset Size: Which wasn't a concern for this assessment since the dataset is quite small.
4) Explainability: A decision tree classifier can be explained to both a non-technical and technical audience.

Normally, I would have selected three to four models from the Supervised Learning-Classification subset of machine learning models. For example, Logistic Regression (classic choice), Support Vector Machine (SVM), Decision Tree Classifier, and Random Forest Classifier. In this way, I could compare results across models and choose the one with the optimal outcome given the application. Also, I would request a colleague to perform some due diligence testing on my models.

The model takes two forms:
1) Raw
2) Optimized

I did this so I could compare the baseline results provided by the raw model with the improved results provided by the optimized model.

The Hyperparameters in my optimized model include: maximum depth, maximum features, minimum leaf samples, and minimum leaf sample splits. These serve to constrain the model which provides a boost in overall performance. It's especially common for tree depth, node samples, and node sample splits to become large which leads to variance/overfitting. As can be observed in the comments, I ran the hyperparameters with various values while calling the dt.bestparams method to arrive at an acceptable selection for use in the optimized model. The hyperparameters were used within the GridSearchCV method which performs a rather exhaustive combinatorial search over five-folds. The downside to Grid Search is the exponential growth that comes with adding too many hyperparameters.

Regularization aims to reduce the complexity of models by introducing a penalty term with the goal of reducing variance/overfitting. A traditional example might include a Regression model regularized with either Lasso, Ridge, or Elastic net (a combination of Lasso and Ridge).
Unfortunately, it’s not that straight forward for our Decision Tree Classifier Model.
That said, the complexity of our Decision Tree Classifier Model can be constrained by using our hyperparameters (maximum depth, maximum features, minimum leaf samples, and minimum leaf sample splits) which ultimately acts a pseudo-regularization parameter for reducing variance/overfitting.

With this in mind, we can effortlessly observe the work of our hyperparameters by performing a visual inspection of the tree structures for both models.
The top visual represents the raw model while the bottom visual represents the optimized model.
We are not concerned with the details of these visuals; but rather, the overall structural reduction observed between the top visual and the bottom visual.

This is what reducing variance/overfitting looks like.

I used K-Fold Cross-Validation to avoid training and testing on the same subsets of data which could have led to variance/overfitting. We can confirm success by observing the nearly similar scores recorded for cross-validation and accuracy in the optimized model results.
K-Fold Cross-Validation requires three steps:
1) A random shuffle of equal size folds.
2) for each fold (k), train the model on all the other folds except for (i) and evaluate the validation error using fold (i).
3) Compute the average of the (k) validation errors from step 2 to get an estimate of the actual error.
k = training data , i = testing data

Model Performance Observations:

• As we might expect with a Decision Tree Classifier, variance/overfitting is observed in both the raw model and the optimized model.
• Large variance/overfitting for the raw model: ~99.50% Training Score Vs. ~85.00% Testing Score.
• Minimal variance/overfitting for the optimized model: ~87.00% Training Score Vs. ~ 85.00% Testing Score.
• Accuracy remains consistent for both models.
• From raw model to optimized model: Precision increases ~3.00%.
• From raw model to optimized model: Recall decreases ~3.00%
• F1 remains consistent for both models

The confusion matrix gives us the following information:
1) The model incorrectly predicts customer cancellation when the customer actually did not cancel for ~2,900 instances. (False Positive, Type I Error)
2) The model incorrectly predicts a customer did not cancel when the customer actually did cancel for ~2,500 instances. (False Negative, Type II Error)
3) The model correctly predicts customer cancellation for ~20,000 instances. (True Positive)
4) The model correctly predicts a customer did not cancel for ~10,000 instances. (True Negative)

The Precision Vs. Recall Trade-Off
There is a natural trade-off between these two measures which can be understood by drawing upon a common real-world analogy. On the one hand, we might have high recall for diagnosing the most patients with disease (X) at the cost of diagnosing disease (X) in some patients that actually don’t have disease (X). On the other hand, we might have high precision for correctly diagnosing a smaller number of overall patients with disease (X) at the cost of not being able to diagnose some patients. This is the classic quantity vs. quality tradeoff that is a normal part of the human experience. Interestingly, this trade-off is reflected in our raw model (to) optimized model results as we observed a precision increase of ~3.00% in tandem with a recall decrease of ~3.00%.

What could we do to further improve the Model?
• Normalize the data.
• Feature selection via pruning or forward/backward stepwise algorithm.
• Continue refining the hyperparameters.
• Use the ROC curve/AUC performance measurements for further insight (note: The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve plots the true positive rate Vs. the false positive rate. The Area Under the Curve (AUC) measures how well the classification model separates classes).
• Train three to four model in parallel to learn more about performance and the dataset.

Business Insights and Recommendations

As shown above, we can predict booking cancellations with ~85% accuracy based on the dataset and selected machine learning model. This could empower decision-makers by providing information and enable us to optimize hotel occupancy; and thus, revenues.

Equally important, we now know that non-refundable deposits are the leading cause of booking cancellations, followed by: Online Travel Agents, lead time, total number of special requests, and local customers. We can utilize this information to propose heuristics that streamline business efficiency and boost business performance.

Here are some examples of how we might be able to use these five attributes to improve business:
1) Use an alternative strategy to hedge against non-refundable deposit cancellations. For example, dynamic pricing that becomes more attractive for last minute bookings.
2) Reformulate the incentive structure for online travel agents so they have more ‘skin in the game’.
3) Determine a maximum lead time for allowing bookings.
4) Incorporate common low-cost special requests into the regular service to reduce the total number of special requests.
5) Offer ‘staycation’ promotions to local customers.

I would recommend an in-depth analysis of the descriptive statistics for each important feature as well as discussing the results with domain expert colleagues to also incorporate the human experience prior to forming business strategy and generating business decisions.

All things considered, we remember the well-known adage, "all models are wrong, but some are useful".
